The heat-kernel already gives the denominator you need.

---

### 1 A uniform lower bound for \(e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\mu_\infty\)

Assume there are constants \(c>0,\;r_0>0,\;\beta\in(0,n]\) such that

\[
\mu_\infty\bigl(B_r(x)\bigr)\;\ge\;c\,r^{\beta}\qquad(0<r<r_0,\;x\in\operatorname{supp}\mu_\infty).
\tag{LB}
\]

Write the Gaussian representation of the mollified measure and restrict the
integral to \(B_{\sqrt{\varepsilon}}(x)\):

\[
e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\mu_\infty(x)
=\frac{1}{(4\pi\varepsilon)^{n/2}}
\int_{B_{\sqrt{\varepsilon}}(x)}\!
e^{-\frac{|x-y|^{2}}{4\varepsilon}}\;d\mu_\infty(y)
\;\ge\;
(4\pi)^{-n/2}\,e^{-1/4}\,c\,\varepsilon^{(\beta-n)/2}.
\]

Hence for all \(0<\varepsilon<\varepsilon_0\)

\[
m(\varepsilon)\;\vcentcolon=\;
\operatorname*{ess\,inf}_{x}e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\mu_\infty(x)
\;\ge\;
c_1\,\varepsilon^{(\beta-n)/2},
\qquad c_1\;=\;(4\pi)^{-n/2}e^{-1/4}c.
\tag{1}
\]

---

### 2 Making the two kernels close

From exponential mixing and heat-kernel contractivity we already have

\[
\|e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\mu_{t(\varepsilon)}
        -e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\mu_\infty\|_{L^\infty}
\;\le\;
C\,e^{-\lambda t(\varepsilon)}.
\tag{2}
\]

Choose

\[
t(\varepsilon)
=\frac{\beta-n+2\sigma}{2\lambda}\,|\log\varepsilon|\quad(\sigma>0),
\tag{3}
\]

so that \(C e^{-\lambda t(\varepsilon)}=\tfrac12 c_1\,
\varepsilon^{(\beta-n)/2+\sigma}\).  
With this choice

\[
e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\mu_{t(\varepsilon)}(x)\;\ge\;
e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\mu_\infty(x)-C e^{-\lambda t(\varepsilon)}
\;\ge\;
\tfrac12 c_1\,\varepsilon^{(\beta-n)/2}
\qquad\text{a.e.}
\tag{4}
\]

---

### 3 Finish the bound on \(\eta(\varepsilon)\)

Denominator (essential infimum of the minimum):

\[
\operatorname{ess\,inf}
\bigl(e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\mu_{t(\varepsilon)}
      \wedge
      e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\mu_\infty\bigr)
\;\ge\;
\tfrac12 c_1\,\varepsilon^{(\beta-n)/2}.
\tag{5}
\]

Plug (2) and (5) into the logarithmic Mean Value Theorem estimate:

\[
\eta(\varepsilon)
\;\le\;
\frac{C\,e^{-\lambda t(\varepsilon)}}
     {\tfrac12 c_1\,\varepsilon^{(\beta-n)/2}}
=\frac{2C}{c_1}\,\varepsilon^{\sigma}.
\]

Because \(\sigma>0\) is arbitrary,

\[
\boxed{\displaystyle
\eta(x)=\lim_{\varepsilon\to0}\eta(\varepsilon)=0\quad\text{in }L^\infty.}
\]

The proof is complete without invoking any notion of “dimension’’—only (LB), exponential mixing, and the heat-kernel contractivity were required.

