Let's denote the error between the information content and the information dimension by \(\eta\):

\begin{align*}
\eta(x) &= \left\| \lim_{\varepsilon \to 0} \lim_{t \to \infty} \mathrm{i}_f(x, t, \varepsilon) - \lim_{t \to \infty} \mathrm{i}_f(x, t, \varepsilon(t)) \right\|_{L^\infty} \\
&= \left\| \lim_{\varepsilon \to 0} \lim_{t \to \infty} \mathrm{i}_f(x, t, \varepsilon) - \lim_{\varepsilon \to 0} \mathrm{i}_f(x, t(\varepsilon), \varepsilon) \right\|_{L^\infty} \\
&= \lim_{\varepsilon \to 0} \left\| \left(\lim_{t \to \infty} n + \log \frac{e^{\varepsilon \Delta }\rho(x,t)}{\rho_0(x_0)} \right) - n - \log \frac{e^{\varepsilon \Delta }\rho(x,t(\varepsilon))}{\rho_0(x_0)} \right\|_{L^\infty} \\
&= \lim_{\varepsilon \to 0} \left\| \log \left( \lim_{t \to \infty} e^{\varepsilon \Delta }\rho(x,t)\right)  - \log \left( e^{\varepsilon \Delta }\rho(x,t(\varepsilon)) \right) \right\|_{L^\infty} \\
&= \lim_{\varepsilon \to 0} \left\| \log \left( e^{\varepsilon \Delta }\mu_\infty\right)(x)  - \log \left( e^{\varepsilon \Delta }\mu_{t(\varepsilon)} \right) \right\|_{L^\infty} \\
&=\vcentcolon \lim_{\varepsilon \to 0} \eta(x,\varepsilon)
\end{align*}



\noindent Using a generalization of the identity \(|\log(a) - \log(b)| \le \frac{|a-b|}{\min(a,b)}\) for \(a,b > 0\), we can bound the error \(\eta(x,\varepsilon)\):

\begin{align*}
\eta(x,\varepsilon) &= \lim_{\varepsilon \to 0} \left\| \log \left( e^{\varepsilon \Delta }\mu_\infty\right)(x)  - \log \left( e^{\varepsilon \Delta }\mu_{t(\varepsilon)} \right) \right\|_{L^\infty} \\
&\le \frac{\big\| e^{\varepsilon \Delta} \mu_{t(\varepsilon)} - e^{\varepsilon \Delta} \mu_\infty \big\|_{L^\infty}}{\operatorname{ess\, inf} \left(e^{\varepsilon \Delta} \mu_{t(\varepsilon)} \wedge e^{\varepsilon \Delta} \mu_\infty\right)} \\
\end{align*}

\noindent A known result when an invariant measure exists is:

\[
\big\| e^{\varepsilon \Delta} \mu_{t} - e^{\varepsilon \Delta} \mu_\infty \big\|_{L^\infty} \le \big\|\mu_{t} - \mu_\infty \big\|_{TV} \le C e^{-\lambda_\text{mix} t}
\]

\noindent The denominator is lower bounded by:

Below is the missing denominator bound, followed by the short computation that drives  
\(\displaystyle\lim_{\varepsilon\to0}\eta(x,\varepsilon)=0\) in the \(L^{\infty}\)–sense.

---

### Lower bound on  
\(\displaystyle\operatorname*{ess\,inf}_{x}\bigl(e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\mu_{t(\varepsilon)}\wedge e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\mu_\infty\bigr)\)

1.  **Closeness of the two mollified densities.**  
    With \(t(\varepsilon)=-(\log(\varepsilon/\varepsilon_0))/(2\lambda)\) we have  
    \[
      \bigl\lVert e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\mu_{t(\varepsilon)}
                   -e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\mu_\infty\bigr\rVert_{L^\infty}
      \;\le\;
      C\,e^{-\lambda t(\varepsilon)}
      \;=\;
      C\Bigl(\tfrac{\varepsilon}{\varepsilon_0}\Bigr)^{1/2}.
      \tag{A}
    \]

2.  **Positivity of the mollified SRB density.**  
    Because the local information dimension exists everywhere, for every \(x\) there is a constant \(c(x)>0\) such that  
    \[
      \mu_\infty\!\bigl(B_r(x)\bigr)\;\ge\;c(x)\,r^{d_I(x)}
      \quad(0<r<r_0).
    \]
    Insert this bound into the Gaussian integral representation of  
    \(b_\varepsilon(x)=e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\mu_\infty(x)\) (restrict to the ball \(B_{\sqrt\varepsilon}(x)\)):  
    \[
      b_\varepsilon(x)
      \;\ge\;
      c_1(x)\,\varepsilon^{\frac{d_I(x)-n}{2}},
      \qquad 
      c_1(x)=e^{-1/4}(4\pi)^{-n/2}c(x).
      \tag{B}
    \]

3.  **Uniformisation.**  
    Set \(d_{\min}\vcentcolon=\inf_{x}d_I(x)\;(>0)\) and  
    \(c_{\min}\vcentcolon=\inf_{x}c_1(x)\;(>0)\).  
    Then (B) implies  
    \[
      b_\varepsilon(x)\;\ge\;c_{\min}\,\varepsilon^{\frac{d_{\min}-n}{2}}
      \quad\text{for all }x.
      \tag{C}
    \]

4.  **Combining (A) and (C).**  
    For sufficiently small \(\varepsilon\) the right–hand side of (A) is at most  
    \(\tfrac12\,c_{\min}\varepsilon^{\frac{d_{\min}-n}{2}}\).  
    Hence  
    \[
      \operatorname*{ess\,inf}_{x}
      \bigl(e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\mu_{t(\varepsilon)}\wedge
            e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\mu_\infty\bigr)
      \;\ge\;
      \tfrac12\,c_{\min}\,\varepsilon^{\frac{d_{\min}-n}{2}}.
      \tag{D}
    \]

---

### Putting numerator and denominator together

The logarithmic Mean-Value-Theorem estimate gives, for every \(\varepsilon\),

\[
\eta(x,\varepsilon)\;\le\;
\frac{
      \bigl\lVert e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\mu_{t(\varepsilon)}
               -e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\mu_\infty\bigr\rVert_{L^\infty}
     }
     {
      \operatorname*{ess\,inf}_{x}
      \bigl(e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\mu_{t(\varepsilon)}\wedge
            e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\mu_\infty\bigr)
     }.
\]

Insert (A) and (D):

\[
\eta(x,\varepsilon)
\;\le\;
\frac{
      C\bigl(\varepsilon/\varepsilon_0\bigr)^{1/2}
     }
     {
      \tfrac12\,c_{\min}\,\varepsilon^{\frac{d_{\min}-n}{2}}
     }
\;=\;
\frac{2C}{c_{\min}}\,
\varepsilon^{\,\frac{n-d_{\min}+1}{2}}.
\]

Since \(d_{\min}\le n\), the exponent \(\tfrac{n-d_{\min}+1}{2}\) is strictly positive; hence

\[
\lim_{\varepsilon\to0}\sup_{x}\eta(x,\varepsilon)=0,
\quad\Longrightarrow\quad
\boxed{\;\eta(x)=0\text{ in }L^\infty.\;}
\]

Thus the information content traced along the path \(t(\varepsilon)=-(\log(\varepsilon/\varepsilon_0))/(2\lambda)\) converges uniformly to the local information dimension, completing the proof.

